[Student "S"]
{Surely this hand will play better in \Ss than in notrump. So you transfer with 2\H and partner bids 2\S.  

Surely this hand will play better in \Ss than in notrump. So you transfer with 2\H and partner bids 2\S. 

You pass. In the old days, before transfers, you would have bid 2\S with this hand as a sign-off. The only difference is that now partner gets to play it.

The contract would be 2\S played by South.

North plays 2\S. East leads the \HQ and West plays the \H9.

Loser List: \S = 2 : \H = 2 : \D = 3 : \C = 0 :: Total = 7

Suppose you win the \HA, play over to the \CQ, then try to get back to your hand with a trump to discard 2 losers on \C A K. If it worked that way it would be fine, but it is very likely that a defender would win their trump Ace, then take their 2 \Hs and 3 \Ds. You could be down one before you even got started.

A better approach is to trade one of your \C winners for a quick discard. Take the \HA, then play  \C A K, discarding a \H from dummy. That will eliminate one \H loser. 

You probably cannot avoid your 3 \D losers, but you may be able to get out with losing a single trump. <b>IF</b> \Ss split 3-2, and <b>IF</b> you can win tricks with both the \SK and \SQ then you will make it. The only way it can happen is if West holds a doubleton \S A x. You must play the first \S from dummy, so ruff a \C to get there, then lead a small \S, putting on your \SQ when West follows low. This wins the trick, (hip-hip), so you now play your \S3, ducking in dummy. When West has to take his \SA, (hooray), you are home-free.

With West holding the \SA, this Plan clearly works.

But, if you need West to hold the \S A x anyway, perhaps that first plan would have worked better. You know, take dummy's \CQ, then play a low \S to get to your hand. 

It depends on West. If he ducked the low \S then you could get <b>TWO</b> discards and make an overtrick.

The method given here gives up the possibility of an overtrick for an improved chance of making the contract. You choose.}
[Play "W"]HQ

